Module org.postgresql.pljava.internal
Package org.postgresql.pljava.jdbc

Class XMLEventToStreamConsumer

java.lang.Object
org.postgresql.pljava.jdbc.XMLEventToStreamConsumer
All Implemented Interfaces:
XMLEventConsumer, XMLStreamConstants
class XMLEventToStreamConsumer extends Object implements XMLEventConsumer, XMLStreamConstants
Consume a stream of StAX XMLEvents, writing them to an XMLStreamWriter.

This entire class would be completely unnecessary if not for the regression in Java 9 and later that leaves XMLOutputFactory.createXMLEventWriter throwing a ClassCastException if passed a StAXResult wrapping an arbitrary XMLStreamWriter implementation, which works perfectly up through Java 8. Java 9 breaks it, demanding this soul-crushing workaround.

Making the best of a bad situation, in reimplementing this, it is possible to honor the distinction between empty elements and start/end tags with nothing in between. An XMLStreamWriter has distinct methods writeStartElement and writeEmptyElement, but the XMLEventWriter API offers no obvious way to pass along that distinction. There is a nonobvious way, though, if the StartElement and EndElement events have parser-supplied Locations, and they are equal (and not 'unknown' in all values).
